April 15 (Reuters) -  U.S. stock index futures edged up on Tuesday after earnings from Coca Cola and Johnson & Johnson and ahead of economic data including inflation and manufacturing. Dow Jones industrial average futures <DJc1> were down 0.10 percent at 16,080, S&P 500 futures <SPc1> were up 0.24 percent at 1,828.8 and Nasdaq 100 futures <NDc1> were up 0.33 percent at 3,481.75. [.N]

** THE COCA-COLA CO <KO.N>, Monday close $38.73, +2.94 pct premarket The beverage giant reported better-than-expected quarterly revenue as strong sales in China more than offset a drop in Europe and flat volumes in North America. [ID:L3N0N72YU]  ** JOHNSON & JOHNSON <JNJ.N>, Monday close $97.14, +2.48 pct premarket The diversified healthcare company on Tuesday reported quarterly earnings well above Wall Street expectations, as strong sales of new prescription drugs offset weak sales of consumer products. [ID:nL2N0N70E6]  ** ZEBRA TECHNOLOGIES CORP <ZBRA.O>, Monday close $68.28, +11.38 pct premarket ** MOTOROLA SOLUTIONS INC <MSI.N>, Monday close $63.78, +1.52 pct premarket   The barcode printer maker said it would buy Motorola Solutions Inc's enterprise business, which makes rugged mobile computers, tablets and barcode scanners, for $3.45 billion in cash. [ID:nL3N0N72O0]  ** AARON'S INC <AAN.N>, Monday close $30.47, -2.20 pct premarket The rent-to-own furniture and electronics retailer rejected a takeover offer from a major shareholder and said it bought retail credit financing firm Progressive Finance Holdings LLC for about $700 million from private equity firm Summit Partners.[ID:nL3N0N72SW]  ** PEP BOYS-MANNY, MOE & JACK <PBY.N>, Monday close $11.97, -5.6 pct after market The auto parts retailer reported a 7 percent drop in fourth-quarter revenue and said weak pricing is expected to hit results in the next quarter as well. [ID:nBw6zMDXda]  ** INFOSYS LTD <INFY.N>, Monday close $55.58, -2.12 pct premarket Staff left India's second largest IT services exporter at an unprecedented pace in the last quarter, worrying its management and raising investors' concerns about its ability to win lucrative contracts even as it posted a higher-than-expected net profit for the period. [ID:nL3N0N70T7]  ** GENERAL ELECTRIC CO <GE.N>, Monday close $25.71, +0.27 pct premarket Chief Executive Jeff Immelt may step down sooner than his expected 20-year tenure, the Wall Street Journal reported, citing people familiar with the company's thinking. [ID:nL3N0N71NQ]  ** HERBALIFE LTD <HLF.N>, Monday close $53.75, +0.8 pct aftermarket   The company was hit with a shareholder class action lawsuit Monday accusing the multilevel-marketing company of failing to disclose to investors that its operations were based on a pyramid scheme. [ID:nL2N0N7049]  ** USEC INC <USU.N>, Monday close $3.47  The uranium supplier said the U.S. Department of Energy has agreed to extend the funding agreement for the company's Ohio-based American Centrifuge project till April 30. [ID:nBwbbPZL6a]  ** SPIRIT AIRLINES INC <SAVE.O>, Monday close $55.61The low-cost carrier said it expected available seat miles (ASMs) to rise 21 percent in the first quarter and 17.2 percent in all of 2014. The company said it expected operating margins to rise 13.2-13.7 percent in the first quarter and 16-18 percent in 2014. [ID:nEOL2rPd9W]  ** SOTHEBY'S <BID.N>, Monday close $40.2  Activist investor Daniel Loeb, who is fighting to win control of three board seats at Sotheby's, on Monday raised the temperature by saying the current board has failed and that its attacks on him are "false" and "misleading." [ID:nL2N0N61PB]  ** MERCK & CO INC <MRK.N>, Monday close $55.57, +0.2 pct after market Merck said the U.S. Food and Drug Administration on Monday approved its grass pollen allergy vaccine, Grastek, for patients aged 5 to 65.  The company, which developed the tablet-based drug with Denmark's ALK Abello <ALKb.CO>, said it expects to launch the treatment in the United States by late April. [ID:nL3N0N646A]   ** INTEL CORP <INTC.O>, Monday close $26.56 Intel is expected to report first-quarter revenue in line with as the PC industry's steep decline shows signs of bottoming out. The chipmaker has been depending on its high-end server chips to make up for struggling PC chip sales and sustain profitability. But demand from server customers was less-than-expected in the December quarter.